  {
    "index": 3,
    "hash": "zGxkzD3JcIcsUkVV7j/GAxYLM6I=",
    "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z",
    "action": {
      "type": "SET_CONTENT",
      "input": {
        "content": "## Testing strategy: two Bee nodes, five dimensions\n\nCollab cannot be faithfully unit-tested alone \u2014 the mesh, ACT, and GSOC paths require real Bee infrastructure. The strategy pairs targeted unit tests with integration runs on **two live Bee nodes**.\n\n### Test dimensions\n\n- **Unit.** Collab-manifest read/write, participant add/remove idempotency, GSOC routing by `collabId` / `writerAddress`.\n- **Integration (two Bee nodes).** A creates drive-level collab with B; verify B receives invitation via PSS; B joins; both users make drive ops and doc ops; verify each sees the other's ops in the operation store within **2 s (GSOC path)** and within the **poll interval (fallback path)**.\n- **Signature attribution.** Every revision arriving on B's side is signed by A's signer, and vice versa, in the toolbar history. No unsigned or mis-attributed ops.\n- **Permission boundary (doc-level collab).** A and B collaborate on doc X only; verify B cannot read other docs in A's drive, and verify B's reactor does not materialize them locally.\n- **Offline resilience.** A goes offline, B makes 10 ops, A comes back, A pulls all 10 ops from B's feed. (No GSOC pings arrived during the offline window, so the poll fallback is doing the work.)\n\nThe two-Bee-node requirement is non-negotiable: a single-node test cannot exercise the cross-peer GSOC path or ACT grantee boundary.",
        "updatedAt": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
      },
      "timestampUtcMs": "2026-05-13T13:00:29.000Z"
    }
  },
